itemize:
\begin{itemize}
\item Any $\mathcal{N}=2$ MESGT is always
invariant under the global R-symmetry
group $SU(2)_{R}$. As mentioned earlier, $SU(2)_{R}$  acts nontrivially only
on the fermions $\Psi_{\mu}^{i}$ and
$\lambda^{i\ensuremath{\tilde{a}}}$. In particular, it does not act on the vector fields
$A_{\mu}^{\ensuremath{\tilde{I}}}$.
\item Any group, $G$, of linear transformations
\begin{equation} \label{hAtrafo}
h^{\ensuremath{\tilde{I}}}\rightarrow {B^{\ensuremath{\tilde{I}}}}_{\ensuremath{\tilde{J}}}h^{\ensuremath{\tilde{J}}}, \quad A_{\mu}^{\ensuremath{\tilde{I}}}\rightarrow
{B^{\ensuremath{\tilde{I}}}}_{\ensuremath{\tilde{J}}}A_{\mu}^{\ensuremath{\tilde{J}}}
\end{equation} that leave the
tensor $C_{\ensuremath{\tilde{I}}\ensuremath{\tilde{J}}\ensuremath{\tilde{K}}}$ invariant
\begin{displaymath}
{B^{\ensuremath{\tilde{I}}'}}_{\ensuremath{\tilde{I}}}{B^{\ensuremath{\tilde{J}}'}}_{\ensuremath{\tilde{J}}}{B^{\ensuremath{\tilde{K}}'}}_{\ensuremath{\tilde{K}}}C_{\ensuremath{\tilde{I}}'\ensuremath{\tilde{J}}'\ensuremath{\tilde{K}}'}
=C_{\ensuremath{\tilde{I}}\ensuremath{\tilde{J}}\ensuremath{\tilde{K}}} \ ,
\end{displaymath}
is automatically a symmetry of the entire Lagrangian (\ref{Lagrange}),
since the latter
is uniquely  determined by the $C_{\ensuremath{\tilde{I}}\ensuremath{\tilde{J}}\ensuremath{\tilde{K}}}$.
These symmetries act as
isometries of the scalar manifold $\mathcal{M}$,
which becomes evident if one rewrites
the kinetic energy term for the scalar fields as \cite{GST1,dWvP1}
\begin{displaymath}
-\frac{1}{2}g_{\ensuremath{\tilde{x}}\ensuremath{\tilde{y}}}(\partial_{\mu}\varphi^{\ensuremath{\tilde{x}}})(\partial^{\mu}
\varphi^{\ensuremath{\tilde{y}}})= \frac{3}{2}C_{\ensuremath{\tilde{I}}\ensuremath{\tilde{J}}\ensuremath{\tilde{K}}}h^{\ensuremath{\tilde{I}}}\partial_{\mu}h^{\ensuremath{\tilde{J}}}
\partial^{\mu}h^{\ensuremath{\tilde{K}}} \ ,
\end{displaymath}
with the $h^{\ensuremath{\tilde{I}}}$ being constrained according to (\ref{hyper}).
